    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, our offensive engine is headlined by **Mickey Moniak** (75.75) and **James Wood** (73.10), who offer the highest ceilings based on favorable park factors and advantageous batting order positioning. **Mickey Moniak** benefits immensely from a 14% park boost, pairing perfectly with a favorable platoon matchup against Mike Burrows. Meanwhile, **James Wood** is our priority leadoff play; his 10% order bonus combined with a strong matchup against Matthew Liberatore makes him a locked-in core piece. **Vinnie Pasquantino** (71.09) also remains a must-start, as he exploits a soft matchup against G. Williams, with a massive 14% dynamic platoon edge driving his projection well above his season baseline.\n\nWe are paying close attention to the impact of today\u2019s wind patterns, which have suppressed scores for several starters like **Gabriel Moreno** and **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**\u2014though **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** maintains a 66.46 score thanks to a significant 11% boost from facing Aaron Civale\u2019s lower-tier skill set. The tightest decision on our bench was **Jose Caballero**, who sat at 47.69. While he offers the elite sprint speed we covet, the combination of a negative platoon dynamic against Civale and the volatility of his projected 8-hole spot pushed him just behind the floor of our utility and middle-infield starters. \n\nRisks today center on the high volume of \"Lineup Pending\" designations, specifically for **Dalton Rushing**, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, **Zach McKinstry**, **Austin Riley**, **Giancarlo Stanton**, **Tyler Soderstrom**, and **Josh Naylor**. Any shift in their placement in the batting order could trigger a re-evaluation of their efficiency scores. Furthermore, while **Corbin Carroll** is a strong play at 61.21, the wind-in warning at his park serves as a cautionary note, though his profile as a base-stealing threat against a slow-delivering Peralta keeps him in the green for our daily aggressive strategy.",
